The ADR has been saved to `ADR-001-notification-architecture.md`.

**Summary of the recommendation:**

| Criterion | Redis Streams (Chosen) | Apache Kafka (Rejected) |
|-----------|----------------------|------------------------|
| **Setup time** | Days (existing infra) | 3-4 weeks (new cluster) |
| **Team fit** | Familiar, low overhead | Zero experience, steep curve |
| **Throughput** | 100K+ msg/s (sufficient) | Millions/sec (overkill) |
| **Exactly-once** | Requires app-level idempotency | Native support |
| **Operations** | Minimal (existing) | Significant (new expertise needed) |
| **Cost** | Included in existing spend | Managed: expensive; Self-hosted: risky |

The decision prioritizes **operational pragmatism** — the 6-person team without infrastructure expertise can deploy Redis Streams safely within 2 weeks, whereas Kafka introduces unacceptable operational risk despite its technical superiority. The exactly-once limitation for billing events is addressed through idempotency keys and consumer-side deduplication, which is a standard pattern for handling this constraint with at-least-once systems.
